\title{Primitive Polynomial and Content of Polynomial}
\author{alex-nelson}
\import{notation}
\date{2025-12-18}
\taxon{definition}

\p{Let #{R} be a [[ra-001Z]], let #{x} be a formal variable. Let #{f(x)\in R[x]} be a nonconstant polynomial. Then we define the \define{Content} of #{f} to be the #{c(f)\in\NonZero{R}} equal to the greatest common divisor of its nonzero coefficients, and the \define{Primitive Part} of #{f} to be the polynomial #{f_{0}\in R[x]} such that #{c(f_{0})=1} and
##{f(x)=c(f)f_{0}(x).}
We say #{f} is \define{Primitive} if #{f=f_{0}}.}